1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:18,376
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa

2
00:00:18,356 --> 00:00:41,243
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa homage to the buddha the blessed noble and fully self-awakened one so greetings to all you revelers in full moon delights so this is uh some of these um

3
00:00:41,542 --> 00:00:43,524
months lend themselves to certain subjects.

4
00:00:43,566 --> 00:00:45,268
So obviously this one is about love.

5
00:00:46,069 --> 00:00:55,981
So I reread, I've read it about five times over the years, Eric Fromm's classic, The Art of Loving.

6
00:00:56,561 --> 00:01:01,408
And some of you might know, definitely worth a read anyway.

7
00:01:01,427 --> 00:01:05,112
And I'm going to, he starts off, but I'm going to turn it into a sort of question.

8
00:01:05,352 --> 00:01:07,094
Like when we do something,

9
00:01:07,632 --> 00:01:11,456
or say something, or think something out of love?

10
00:01:12,197 --> 00:01:17,621
Do we do it in order to love, in order to develop our love, or do we do it to be loved?

11
00:01:18,102 --> 00:01:19,563
That's a cheeky one, that, right?

12
00:01:20,444 --> 00:01:25,430
So then he talks about why we need this love.

13
00:01:25,489 --> 00:01:27,871
And of course, it's a psychoanalysis thing.

14
00:01:28,992 --> 00:01:37,621
And when we're born, you know, for those first few months or so, there's no separation between us and our mothers.

15
00:01:39,052 --> 00:01:43,099
And so that's really a halcyon pierce, a heavenly state to be in.

16
00:01:43,599 --> 00:01:51,250
And then, of course, the separation starts, which is needed for the child to become a little independent being.

17
00:01:51,831 --> 00:01:54,313
But that separation is a sense of loss.

18
00:01:55,094 --> 00:02:04,587
And according to psychoanalysis, that's what produces our loneliness in life, because we want to get back to that wonderful place we were when we were babies.

19
00:02:06,762 --> 00:02:24,536
From the Buddha's point of view, from the Dharma's point of view, rather, of course, it's more to do with the essential relationship that we make with this psychophysical organism that we call the self.

20
00:02:25,538 --> 00:02:29,444
And the self knows that it is

21
00:02:29,627 --> 00:02:30,549
unstable.

22
00:02:30,729 --> 00:02:34,633
It comes to know that it's not secure.

23
00:02:34,693 --> 00:02:43,003
So the fundamental position from a dharma point of view is this feeling of unsafety.

24
00:02:43,784 --> 00:02:45,948
And because of that, we start collecting things.

25
00:02:47,468 --> 00:02:49,611
And that's the first thing that the Buddha talks about.

26
00:02:50,092 --> 00:02:53,477
It's translated as greed, but it's much better to see it as acquisitiveness.

27
00:02:55,218 --> 00:02:56,539
So we acquire things.

28
00:02:56,620 --> 00:02:59,584
And there are four major areas where we do that, of course.

29
00:02:59,647 --> 00:03:03,957
Rich, you know, I want to be rich like loads of money, like Scrooge.

30
00:03:04,639 --> 00:03:06,905
And the more I have, the safer I feel.

31
00:03:07,125 --> 00:03:09,872
You know, if I've got a million pound in the bank, I feel really safe.

32
00:03:11,936 --> 00:03:15,243
And then there's power.

33
00:03:15,831 --> 00:03:20,478
Control, control over our lives, control over people makes us feel safe.

34
00:03:20,518 --> 00:03:21,400
We're in charge.

35
00:03:22,080 --> 00:03:25,164
That's also can be a real pain.

36
00:03:26,165 --> 00:03:31,933
And then there's pleasure, of course, you know, seeking just people who just want one experience after the other.

37
00:03:32,093 --> 00:03:34,777
You know, been there, got the T-shirt, all that sort of stuff.

38
00:03:35,177 --> 00:03:42,328
Foodies, you know, who live, who live for the next exciting diet or menu rather.

39
00:03:43,050 --> 00:03:49,585
And then finally, there's those who seek to be appreciated, seek to be praised.

40
00:03:49,945 --> 00:03:52,491
And that's usually we're seeking some sort of fame.

41
00:03:52,551 --> 00:04:00,229
OK, so here we're dealing with fame or the desire to be loved.

42
00:04:00,248 --> 00:04:00,468
Yeah.

43
00:04:03,014 --> 00:04:09,145
Now, that would be, of course, also a cause of loneliness.

44
00:04:09,306 --> 00:04:09,546
Yeah.

45
00:04:09,987 --> 00:04:18,846
The fact that when we when we feel lonely, then we have these little words going on in our heads about how useless we are and horrible.

46
00:04:19,567 --> 00:04:34,329
And what we do, we tend to reinforce that by forming friendships, by, so we say, padding out our friendship, friendships by making sure that they are, you know, stable friendships.

47
00:04:34,569 --> 00:04:37,052
We don't want to lose them because then we'd feel really lonely.

48
00:04:38,894 --> 00:04:43,281
But that unfortunately is a bad strategy because what it does is it makes us dependent on them.

49
00:04:43,884 --> 00:04:56,137
And what it means is that when we have our self-worth or self-esteem is dependent on what other people think about us or what they say about us, how they treat us.

50
00:04:56,937 --> 00:05:01,182
And therefore, you know, sometimes you feel pretty rotten if you do that.

51
00:05:02,863 --> 00:05:05,425
And of course, people whom you love disappear.

52
00:05:05,586 --> 00:05:08,689
They either leave you or they get fed up with you and some of them die.

53
00:05:08,730 --> 00:05:11,192
So they're nothing special.

54
00:05:11,475 --> 00:05:14,201
Nothing is to be taken for granted.

55
00:05:14,322 --> 00:05:17,247
So there's always that little sense of anxiety of loss.

56
00:05:18,329 --> 00:05:23,120
Anything you become attached to is going to create some anxiety of loss.

57
00:05:25,605 --> 00:05:28,692
And the other thing we do, of course, is to seek distraction.

58
00:05:29,228 --> 00:05:30,408
And I'll come to that in a minute.

59
00:05:31,690 --> 00:05:35,836
So the best strategy is actually to love, right, to come from the position of love.

60
00:05:36,216 --> 00:05:42,464
So when you come from a position of love, you immediately fill yourself with good feelings, good feelings about yourself.

61
00:05:43,625 --> 00:05:56,502
And that sense of self-worth, self-esteem comes naturally when we behave from a position of love and all the other positions, social virtues of compassion, joy, etc.,

62
00:05:58,742 --> 00:06:06,935
So how do we purify our love?

63
00:06:07,757 --> 00:06:25,223
First of all, it's to recognize that this thing about the self and it's feeling lonely and it's needed and it's neediness, that has to be recognized so that when we are doing something, we've got to see these little background voices

64
00:06:25,877 --> 00:06:32,444
In the Buddhist teachings, they're known as latent tendencies, the anusaya, the latent tendencies.

65
00:06:32,464 --> 00:06:34,367
So they're always there, ready to be fired.

66
00:06:35,127 --> 00:06:44,517
And in psychology, they'd call it sort of subconscious motivations.

67
00:06:45,038 --> 00:06:47,940
So that's where we get the idea of Freudian slips.

68
00:06:48,461 --> 00:06:54,567
See, something's happening in the back of the mind, we're not recognizing it, and it comes out in a slip that makes us feel embarrassed.

69
00:06:56,336 --> 00:07:09,228
So when we're about to do something or say something or even think something, you've always got to be aware of this little other dialogue that's going on.

70
00:07:11,271 --> 00:07:22,362
So it might be, for instance, well, I'm going to do your garden and I hope the background little voice is saying, and you'll come and do mine when I need it.

71
00:07:23,404 --> 00:07:25,581
Or I know you'll really love me after this.

72
00:07:25,600 --> 00:07:27,576
You'll really appreciate my friendship.

73
00:07:28,112 --> 00:07:31,137
So there's always these little things going on in the background.

74
00:07:31,357 --> 00:07:33,699
And it's a case really of making those conscious.

75
00:07:34,459 --> 00:07:37,723
Now, as soon as they become conscious, they lose power over you.

76
00:07:38,704 --> 00:07:46,574
So if you remember, after the Buddha was fully liberated, there were seven years it said that Mara chased him with his three daughters.

77
00:07:47,315 --> 00:07:49,999
So sensual desire, sexual desire.

78
00:07:50,399 --> 00:07:53,562
And if you don't know the third one, I'll leave you to guess it.

79
00:07:54,589 --> 00:07:59,487
And after seven years, he sort of began to go away, you see.

80
00:07:59,526 --> 00:08:00,771
And he sort of said, what's happening?

81
00:08:00,790 --> 00:08:01,954
He said, well, the Buddha sees me.

82
00:08:02,074 --> 00:08:02,637
He sees me.

83
00:08:03,238 --> 00:08:04,704
He says, well, give us a bit more time.

84
00:08:04,764 --> 00:08:07,333
He says, no, he says, after seven years.

85
00:08:08,545 --> 00:08:11,968
I'm not going to get through to the Buddha.

86
00:08:12,370 --> 00:08:23,004
So as soon as we see these little conversations coming from the self, the neediness of the self, the wanting to be loved, they don't have power over us.

87
00:08:23,524 --> 00:08:29,591
And we then reestablish our commitment to doing something from the heart of love.

88
00:08:30,617 --> 00:08:34,562
And that's how we begin to purify our hearts.

89
00:08:35,264 --> 00:08:40,551
Now, the purification of the heart demands a lessening of the self.

90
00:08:41,793 --> 00:08:47,340
So therefore, itself is a path of love, is a path of liberation, rather, excuse me.

91
00:08:47,360 --> 00:08:51,725
The path of purification is itself a path of liberation.

92
00:08:52,586 --> 00:08:59,375
Normally, of course, we put the accent on insight, on seeing things, which is absolutely necessary as well.

93
00:08:59,913 --> 00:09:04,043
But with the path of love, this is the process.

94
00:09:04,102 --> 00:09:09,476
You're constantly purifying your intentions, coming from the heart.

95
00:09:10,499 --> 00:09:14,850
And it's funny, there was...

96
00:09:16,601 --> 00:09:21,427
There's always an effort in philosophy to give you reasons.

97
00:09:21,447 --> 00:09:30,957
There's not time to go into the way that philosophers think about ethical behaviour, love, compassion and joy and all that.

98
00:09:31,298 --> 00:09:34,361
They try to give us rational reasons.

99
00:09:35,163 --> 00:09:42,812
But the great Scottish philosopher, Hume, and I've heard him called the philosopher's philosopher,

100
00:09:42,792 --> 00:09:50,982
says that whenever he looked into an act of goodwill, always he didn't find a reason at the bottom of it, but he found was a sentiment.

101
00:09:51,543 --> 00:09:55,048
And that's his word for something that arises out of the heart.

102
00:09:56,030 --> 00:10:06,504
And Confucius said that the ground of a harmonious society was benevolence and concern, love and compassion.

103
00:10:07,206 --> 00:10:07,787
So

104
00:10:08,357 --> 00:10:11,541
Everything around love always begins in the heart.

105
00:10:12,121 --> 00:10:15,345
Now, the only problem is that it's not always a feeling.

106
00:10:15,845 --> 00:10:21,791
You don't have to feel loving in order to act from a position of goodwill.

107
00:10:22,471 --> 00:10:32,402
So, for instance, a surgeon who's operating, I doubt if they feel some great big gushing love towards their patient.

108
00:10:32,902 --> 00:10:34,744
I mean, their attention is on what they're doing.

109
00:10:35,024 --> 00:10:37,706
They should be equanimous, calm, cool.

110
00:10:38,041 --> 00:10:38,341
Right.

111
00:10:39,965 --> 00:10:45,053
So, again, when we say the heart, we're really talking about attitude.

112
00:10:45,534 --> 00:10:47,038
We're not talking about feeling.

113
00:10:47,278 --> 00:10:50,683
The feeling is sometimes there and it sometimes isn't.

114
00:10:50,725 --> 00:10:51,907
That's important.

115
00:10:53,369 --> 00:11:01,264
OK, so that that gives us some idea as to how to make ourselves, how to make our acts of love.

116
00:11:01,530 --> 00:11:07,457
the way we speak and the way we think, coming from the heart of love, more and more pure.

117
00:11:08,099 --> 00:11:10,422
But let's just say just a word about loneliness.

118
00:11:13,184 --> 00:11:26,581
Now, when we feel lonely, it's a bit of a downer for the self because the language is something like, nobody loves me who could love me.

119
00:11:26,961 --> 00:11:27,942
I mean, I'm horrible.

120
00:11:29,256 --> 00:11:34,702
And all that sort of really, really upsetting talk.

121
00:11:35,023 --> 00:11:36,445
So we try to escape that.

122
00:11:36,625 --> 00:11:41,551
As soon as you feel lonely, as soon as it actually just drips into consciousness, off we go.

123
00:11:41,610 --> 00:11:49,139
We turn on the TV, get onto social media, open a new packet of biscuits, anything but feel the loneliness.

124
00:11:50,340 --> 00:11:56,527
And that's, of course, why we don't like to tell people we feel lonely, because what we're saying to them is that we're not loved.

125
00:11:56,866 --> 00:11:58,369
We're not appreciated.

126
00:11:59,293 --> 00:12:00,979
So it's a difficult one for us.

127
00:12:01,681 --> 00:12:11,548
Now, if by trying to escape it, of course, it still remains there as one of these anusaya, as one of these latent tendencies.

128
00:12:12,202 --> 00:12:20,671
And what it's going to do is going to make you overact your love to other people so that you can prove that you are appreciated, right?

129
00:12:20,890 --> 00:12:33,943
You're going to be overly joyous at people's success just so they know that you are joyous and that you are to be praised because of that and that appreciated and loved.

130
00:12:35,205 --> 00:12:40,809
So you've got to tackle the loneliness in its rawness, okay?

131
00:12:41,784 --> 00:12:44,008
And this is what Vipassana teaches us.

132
00:12:44,548 --> 00:12:48,414
So we go into the mental state, the feel of it.

133
00:12:48,815 --> 00:12:50,057
And you have to have the patience.

134
00:12:50,076 --> 00:12:51,078
You have to be open to it.

135
00:12:51,538 --> 00:12:58,629
And it helps to have a sense of care towards it, a sense of wanting to...

136
00:12:58,980 --> 00:13:01,284
wanting to heal the heart of it.

137
00:13:02,005 --> 00:13:06,111
And that gives you a right attitude towards the feeling of loneliness.

138
00:13:06,373 --> 00:13:07,754
But you still have to go in there.

139
00:13:08,296 --> 00:13:11,220
You have to sink into it and feel the raw feelings.

140
00:13:11,980 --> 00:13:15,746
And of course, what you're doing is you're opening up to your heart.

141
00:13:15,807 --> 00:13:17,330
The heart wants to speak to you.

142
00:13:17,831 --> 00:13:21,275
It speaks in feelings, in mental states.

143
00:13:21,660 --> 00:13:26,009
And in so doing, what you're doing is we're letting off that steam.

144
00:13:26,370 --> 00:13:31,321
We're allowing that turbulence to manifest as turbulence, as energy.

145
00:13:31,780 --> 00:13:35,308
And therefore, it's exhausting itself, just like anything else.

146
00:13:35,389 --> 00:13:37,894
If you go for a run, at the end of it, you feel exhausted.

147
00:13:38,375 --> 00:13:41,981
So if you give the heart a run, it'll feel exhausted.

148
00:13:42,518 --> 00:13:49,124
And now the really important thing is, if you can, see, this is a really important thing.

149
00:13:49,144 --> 00:13:56,230
If you can to stay to the very last sensation caused by that loneliness, right?

150
00:13:56,470 --> 00:14:00,533
Because if you stay there, you might see the transformation.

151
00:14:01,235 --> 00:14:02,895
And that energy is never lost.

152
00:14:02,956 --> 00:14:05,398
It always transforms towards its opposite.

153
00:14:05,859 --> 00:14:11,884
And what you may experience is a sense of wonderful relief and peacefulness.

154
00:14:12,116 --> 00:14:20,506
But also, to your great surprise, it might burst out into this universal love for all beings.

155
00:14:20,866 --> 00:14:23,529
It's quite remarkable what will happen if you stay to the end.

156
00:14:24,171 --> 00:14:33,201
You don't have to stay to the end for this technique to allow the heart to purify itself.

157
00:14:33,421 --> 00:14:36,504
But if you do, it gives you real confidence because now you know

158
00:14:36,956 --> 00:14:43,102
that all these negative mental states are always moving towards the opposites.

159
00:14:43,663 --> 00:14:45,304
No energy is lost.

160
00:14:46,746 --> 00:14:55,215
And of course, that doesn't mean to say that when they are their opposites, when you do feel love, these mental states can be developed indefinitely.

161
00:14:56,537 --> 00:15:04,784
So in other words, after this year of real commitment, you should be constantly sailing in a piece of joyous love.

162
00:15:04,804 --> 00:15:05,765
No doubt about it.

163
00:15:08,361 --> 00:15:16,903
Unfortunately, this universal love that we're trying to get to, this sort of a love which is above

164
00:15:17,659 --> 00:15:23,707
any love to do with attachments is something we have to develop.

165
00:15:24,009 --> 00:15:27,352
All these other loves, if you think about it, come naturally.

166
00:15:28,254 --> 00:15:32,299
I mean, there's a natural loving of parents towards their children.

167
00:15:32,841 --> 00:15:35,845
You don't organize yourself.

168
00:15:35,865 --> 00:15:38,427
You don't sort of set yourself up to fall in love.

169
00:15:38,849 --> 00:15:40,250
You just fall in love.

170
00:15:41,832 --> 00:15:43,195
You meet somebody.

171
00:15:43,511 --> 00:15:51,619
and you like them, and before you know it, you fall in love, or you've developed a friendship because of that sort of connection between two hearts.

172
00:15:54,322 --> 00:16:06,572
All these types of love are just part of our natural human nature, but to lift it into this universal love, this meta, takes effort.

173
00:16:06,753 --> 00:16:10,937
You've got to lift yourself out of that stuff and really make an effort to

174
00:16:11,288 --> 00:16:14,311
Open up your heart to all beings in all directions.

175
00:16:16,211 --> 00:16:17,552
So that's really the final thing.

176
00:16:17,592 --> 00:16:25,240
So the question then is, to love or to be loved, right?

177
00:16:25,259 --> 00:16:27,062
Am I Shakespeare and Hamlet?

178
00:16:27,361 --> 00:16:28,143
That's the question.

179
00:16:28,482 --> 00:16:35,428
To love or to be loved in terms of our daily activity, in terms of our spiritual practice.

180
00:16:36,250 --> 00:16:41,193
And if we keep an eye on these anusaya, these latent tendencies,

181
00:16:41,477 --> 00:16:42,739
We'll get a hang of it, you see.

182
00:16:43,480 --> 00:16:55,554
It means that you've got to have a slightly more spacious awareness, an awareness which is not only about what's out there, but a constant sort of inner awareness.

183
00:16:56,154 --> 00:16:58,477
You know all the time how you're feeling.

184
00:16:58,778 --> 00:17:01,100
It's just there in the sort of background.

185
00:17:01,321 --> 00:17:07,208
And when something moves, an irritation or something like that, you become aware of it.

186
00:17:07,808 --> 00:17:11,333
And because you're aware of it, it no longer has control over you.

187
00:17:11,734 --> 00:17:19,487
And you can just either park it so you're not pushing it away with fear or with aversion.

188
00:17:19,666 --> 00:17:21,190
So those are suppressive measures.

189
00:17:21,630 --> 00:17:28,641
You're just putting it to the side and reestablishing your attitude, your act of will.

190
00:17:29,462 --> 00:17:29,762
OK.

191
00:17:31,506 --> 00:17:32,007
I think that's it.

192
00:17:32,047 --> 00:17:32,667
I think I've done it.

193
00:17:33,167 --> 00:17:35,531
So I can only hope.

194
00:17:35,663 --> 00:17:48,913
My words have been of some assistance that by your severe practice of goodwill and concern, you will be liberated from all sufferings sooner rather than later.

